Predicting Probability of Hailstorms Using Time Series Forecasting¶

Jessica Manko
GEOG5990 Final Project
University of Colorado Denver
Spring 2020

Introduction¶

Severe weather is a meteorological phenomena with the potential to cause damage. Types of severe weather phenomena vary based on the latitude, altitude, topography, seasonal, and atmospheric conditions. Hail is a form of precipitation consisting of solid ice that forms inside thunderstorm updrafts. Hail is possible within most thunderstorms depending on conditions. Hail can cause billions of dollars of damage to structures, crops and livestock. There are patterns associated with when and where hailstorms tend to occur based on time of day and season in the year. It is useful to accurately forecast when these events will occur to relay warnings and prepare to minimize damages.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's (NOAA) Severe Weather Data Inventory (SWDI) is an integrated database of severe weather records for the United States (US). The National Weather Service (NWS) Doppler (NEXRAD) radar system estimates the intensity, position, velocity, and type of moisture in the atmosphere. Each radar site includes equipment and software that searches this basic precipitation data for patterns that estimate the presence of various kinds of severe weather events.

The dataset used for this project is a product of the NEXRAD radar system and consists of time series data of probability of hail, probability of severe hail, and maximum size of hail for different locations in the US.

Time series is a collection of data points collected at constant time intervals. The time dimension adds an explicit order dependence between observations. Most time series exhibit seasonality trends, particularly within weather. Time series forecasting can be applied to analyze long term trends and predict future events. In this analysis, the ARIMA and Prophet models are used to forecast probability of hail.

Data Exploration¶

This data is a product of NOAA's National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI). This dataset covers hail detections from 2015. This includes the probability of a weather event as well as the size and severity of hail. This helps understand potential damage to property and injury to people. Records are event-level records. Individual storm cells with a high probability of yielding hail are included in this dataset: a total of 1,048,575 rows with 10 columns.
Columns consist of: Time, Lon, Lat, WSR_ID, CELL_ID, Range, Azimuth, Probability, Severe Probability, and Max Size. According to NOAA, these are the definitions of the columns:
WSR_ID - "NEXRAD or TDWR SITE ID"
CELL_ID - "CELL ID UNIQUE TO RADAR SITE"
PROB - "PROBABILITY OF HAIL [PERCENT]"
SEVPROB - "PROB. OF SEVERE HAIL [PERCENT]"
MAXSIZE - "MAX SIZE [IN]"

Goal¶

The goal of this project is to run a time series prediction on the probability of hail events occurring using the Prophet and ARIMA models.

Data Preprocessing¶

This is a large dataset with 1,048,575 records, so I decided to subset the first 20,000 to reduce model runtime and memory issues. I looked at the data properties and cleaned up the data by removing null values and dropping duplicates. I ran some descriptive statistics to better understand the data. I then created a datetime index to run the time series prediction and subset the data frame to the columns I needed to run analysis. I chose to trim some sparse data away and focus on events after 01-03-2015. I subset the datetime index to create a column for hour for future analysis.

Methods¶

Predicting Based on Seconds¶

ARIMA Model¶

One of the most common methods used in time series forecasting is known as the ARIMA model, which stands for AutoregRessive Integrated Moving Average. ARIMA is a model that can be fitted to time series data in order to better understand or predict future points in the series. Parameters include:
p: The number of lag observations included in the model, or lag order.
d: The number of times that the raw observations or degree of differencing.
q: The size of the moving average window, or order of moving average.

In [16]:
#separate training data before 01-04 and test data after 01-04
train = df.loc[ : '2015-01-04 08:00:00']
test = df.loc['2015-01-04 08:00:00': ]

# ARIMA
model = ARIMA(train["PROB"], order=(4,1,7))
model_fit = model.fit(disp=0)
print(model_fit.summary())
predictions = pd.DataFrame(model_fit.forecast(len(test))[0])
predictions.index = test.index

#calculate rmse
rmse = np.sqrt(((predictions[0] - test['PROB'])**2).mean())
print(rmse)

#plot
ax = plt.axes([0, 0, 8, 2])
ax.plot(train["PROB"], color='blue')
ax.plot(test["PROB"], color='lightblue')
ax.plot(predictions, color='red', linewidth=1)

# plot residual errors
residuals = pd.DataFrame(model_fit.resid)
residuals.plot()
plt.show()
residuals.plot(kind='kde')
plt.show()
print(residuals.describe())

Prophet Model¶

Prophet is a procedure created by Facebook for forecasting time series data based on an additive model where non-linear trends are fit with yearly, weekly, and daily seasonality. Prophet is an additive model incorporating trend, seasonality, effects of holidays or large events, and error. In this scenario, trend is most representative of the data and seasonality would be useful for longer-term data.

In [17]:
# Run fbprophet for prediction
# Prophet requires columns ds (Date) and y (probability)
train['ds'], train['y'] = train['DATE'],  train['PROB']
test['ds'], test['y'] = test['DATE'],  test['PROB']

# Make the prophet model and fit on the data
model2 = fbprophet.Prophet(changepoint_prior_scale=0.15)
model2_fit = model2.fit(train)

# Make predictions
predictions2 = model2.predict(test)['yhat']
predictions2.index = test.index

#calculate rmse
rmse = np.sqrt(((predictions2[0] - test['PROB'])**2).mean())
print(rmse)

#plot
ax2 = plt.axes([0, 0, 8, 2])
ax2.plot(train["PROB"], color='blue')
ax2.plot(test["PROB"], color='lightblue')
ax2.plot(predictions2, color='red', linewidth=1)

Predicting Based on Minutes¶

In [18]:
# test on coarser time resolution of minute 
# resample data and group by minute
by_minute = df.index.year.astype(str).str.cat([x.astype(str).str.zfill(2) for x in [ df.index.month, df.index.day, df.index.hour,df.index.minute ]])
df["by_minute"] = pd.to_datetime(by_minute, format="%Y%m%d%H%M")
df = df.groupby("by_minute").mean()

Results¶

The results of the models running based on seconds did not accurately represent future probability of hail. In the graphs above, the dark blue area represents training data, light blue area represents test data, and the red line represents the predicted time series. The prediction line is similar for both the ARIMA and Prophet models. This prediction line is not much better than drawing a line at the mean

The Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) was used to evaluate how accurately the models predicted the response. RMSE is the square root of the variance of the residuals indicating how close the observed data points are to the models predicted values. The ARIMA model had a RMSE of 15.17 and Prophet had a RMSE of 15.33. While lower values of RMSE indicate better fit, these two values are nearly identical so the models performed with similar accuracy.

The mean probability of hail was 33.5%, the standard deviation was 16.2%, and the range was 10%-95%. According to the RMSE, there was approximately a 15% error for both models. Compared to the standard deviation of 16.2%, errors of the models are only ~0.8% better than the error of a horizontal line at the mean.

Resampling the data to a coarser time scale of minutes and reducing the training data time frame produced slightly more accurate results. The RMSE of ARIMA was 11.61% and RMSE of Prophet was 10.88%.

Throughout the analysis process, I adjusted the parameters of the models to experiment with different prediction outcomes. Zooming into a smaller prediction period was important because the data had such a fine resolution of seconds. Resampling the data to a coarser time scale of minutes and shortening the training period yielded more accurate results. Running the models on shorter time frames and continuing to resample to a coarser time scale of hours or days would forecast more accurate probability further out into the future.

Conclusion¶

The goal of the analysis was to run a time series prediction on the probability of hail events occurring using the Prophet and ARIMA models. This project created a framework to preprocess, visualize, and apply a machine learning model for prediction on time series data. Key insights gained included the workflow of running time series prediction and understanding the algorithms within the models.

Limitations within the data include possible spatial inaccuracies with NEXRAD Radar as it decreases with range from Radar sites. Within the analysis, limitations include total spatial consolidation where the model was averaging hail probability for the entire US. The data available was only for January-April and time stamps for records were by the second. The subset I created was only for a couple of days in January to reduce memory.

Recommendations include smoothing out the prediction and resampling the data to a coarser time resolution of hours or days. In addition, it would be interesting to observe how changing the training and test date periods and adjusting the parameters of the models would affect the results. In the future, I would reduce the training data and test data time periods to run the prediction models. These methods could be duplicated to perform time series forecasting on different datasets for future work.
